[2] Cholera: Mozambique (Zambézia)
Date: Mon 13 Jun 2022
Source: Visao Saude [in Portuguese, machine trans., edited]
https://visao.sapo.pt/visaosaude/2022-06-13-provincia-do-centro-de-mocambique-com-cumulativo-de-139-casos-de-colera-desde-declaracao-de-surto/


Health authorities in the province of Zambézia, in central Mozambique, have registered 139 cases of cholera since the announcement, in May [2022], of the outbreak of the disease in the city of Quelimane, with no deaths, announced an official source.

"As of Friday [10 Jun 2022] we had a cumulative 139 cases in Quelimane," said Isaías Marcos, head of health services in Zambézia, quoted by the Mozambican Information Agency (AIM). According to the official, 134 patients were discharged from hospital, and 5 are still hospitalized, and should also be discharged.

Isaías Marcos also warned of the occurrence of other diarrheal diseases, calling for preventive measures to be taken, including "correct handwashing, promotion of community cleaning days, and combating open defecation. A redoubled effort is needed to contain the spread of waterborne diseases", he stressed.

In May [2022], health authorities in Zambézia declared an outbreak of cholera in Quelimane, the provincial capital, after 3 years without the disease.

Cholera is a disease that causes severe diarrhea, which is treatable, but which can cause death from dehydration if not promptly addressed, being caused, in large part, by the ingestion of food and water contaminated by lack of sanitation networks.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED Rapporteur Mahmoud Orabi

